    <section id="sexagenary-cycle">
      <h2>The Sexagenary Cycle (<span class="chinese-char">六十干支</span> <span class="pinyin">Liùshí Gānzhī</span>)</h2>

      <div class="stat-highlight">
        <div class="stat-highlight-number">60</div>
        <div class="stat-highlight-text">
          <strong>Unique combinations</strong> from pairing Yang stems with Yang branches and Yin with Yin. The cycle repeats every 60 years, months, days, and double-hours.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="comparison-grid">
        <div class="comparison-card comparison-card--gold">
          <h3>First Combination</h3>
          <p><strong>Jiǎzǐ</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">甲子</span> <span class="pinyin">Jiǎzǐ</span>) — Yang Wood Rat. The cycle opens with this combination and is sometimes called the "Jiazi cycle."</p>
        </div>
        <div class="comparison-card comparison-card--gold">
          <h3>2026 Example</h3>
          <p><strong>Bǐngwǔ</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">丙午</span> <span class="pinyin">Bǐngwǔ</span>) — Yang Fire Horse. The 43rd combination, basis for <a href="/bazi/">BaZi</a> year pillar calculations.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="lunisolar">
      <h2>Lunisolar Mechanics</h2>

      <p>The Chinese calendar is neither purely lunar nor purely solar &mdash; it is a <strong>lunisolar</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">陰陽合曆</span> <span class="pinyin">Yīnyáng Hélì</span>) system that weaves both together. Think of it as two clocks running simultaneously: one tracks the moon, the other tracks the sun. Together they produce a calendar that stays aligned with both celestial cycles and the seasons.</p>

      <div class="comparison-grid">
        <div class="comparison-card comparison-card--positive">
          <h3>Lunar Component (<span class="chinese-char">陰曆</span> <span class="pinyin">Yīnlì</span>)</h3>
          <p>Each month begins on a <strong>new moon</strong> (the day the moon is invisible) and lasts until the next new moon &mdash; either 29 days (a &ldquo;short month,&rdquo; <span class="chinese-char">小月</span> <span class="pinyin">xiǎoyuè</span>) or 30 days (a &ldquo;long month,&rdquo; <span class="chinese-char">大月</span> <span class="pinyin">dàyuè</span>). The mid-month full moon falls around the 15th, which is why the <strong>Mid-Autumn Festival</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">中秋節</span> <span class="pinyin">Zhōngqiūjié</span>) is always on the 15th of the 8th month &mdash; the moon is guaranteed to be full.</p>
          <p>Twelve lunar months total only about <strong>354 days</strong>, which is roughly 11 days shorter than the solar year. Without correction, the calendar would drift: after just three years, the &ldquo;first month of spring&rdquo; would arrive in mid-winter. The solution is the <strong>intercalary month</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">閏月</span> <span class="pinyin">rùnyuè</span>): approximately 7 times every 19 years (the Metonic cycle), an extra month is inserted to resynchronise the calendar with the seasons.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="comparison-card comparison-card--positive">
          <h3>Solar Component (<span class="chinese-char">陽曆</span> <span class="pinyin">Yánglì</span>)</h3>
          <p>The <strong>24 Solar Terms</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">節氣</span> <span class="pinyin">Jiéqì</span>) divide the sun&rsquo;s annual journey along the ecliptic into 24 segments of approximately 15 days each. Unlike the lunar months, these are tied directly to the sun&rsquo;s position &mdash; so <em>Lìchūn</em> (<span class="chinese-char">立春</span> <span class="pinyin">Lìchūn</span>, Start of Spring) always falls around <strong>February 4</strong>, and the <strong>Winter Solstice</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">冬至</span> <span class="pinyin">Dōngzhì</span>) always falls around <strong>December 22</strong>, regardless of which lunar month it is.</p>
          <p>The Solar Terms serve as the &ldquo;anchor&rdquo; that prevents the lunar months from drifting. The rule is elegant: if a lunar month contains no <strong>Qì</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">中氣</span> <span class="pinyin">Zhōngqì</span>, major solar term), it becomes the intercalary month. For example, in <strong>2025</strong> there is a leap sixth month (<span class="chinese-char">閏六月</span> <span class="pinyin">Rùn Liùyuè</span>) because the extra lunar month between the 6th and 7th months lacks a major solar term.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout-box callout-box--jade">
        <div class="callout-icon">💡</div>
        <div class="callout-content">
          <h3>A Practical Example: Why Does Chinese New Year Move?</h3>
          <p>Chinese New Year falls on the <strong>second new moon after the Winter Solstice</strong>. Since lunar months don&rsquo;t perfectly align with the solar year, the date shifts between <strong>January 21 and February 20</strong> on the Gregorian calendar. In <strong>2025</strong>, Chinese New Year was on <strong>January 29</strong>; in <strong>2026</strong> it falls on <strong>February 17</strong>. The solar anchor (Winter Solstice) keeps the range bounded &mdash; without it, the new year would drift through all seasons like the Islamic Ramadan does.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Gregorian vs. Chinese Calendar &mdash; A Quick Comparison</h3>
      <table class="elements-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Gregorian (Western)</th><th>Chinese Lunisolar</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Basis</td><td>Solar only</td><td>Lunar months + Solar terms</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Month length</td><td>28&ndash;31 days (arbitrary)</td><td>29&ndash;30 days (tied to moon phases)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Year length</td><td>365 or 366 days</td><td>353&ndash;355 days (ordinary) or 383&ndash;385 days (leap year)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Leap correction</td><td>1 extra day every 4 years</td><td>1 extra <em>month</em> ~7 times per 19 years</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Full moon</td><td>Irregular dates</td><td>Always around the 15th of each month</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Seasonal alignment</td><td>Fixed by design</td><td>Maintained by the 24 Solar Terms</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section id="naming-history">
      <h2>What&rsquo;s in a Name? The Naming History of the Chinese Calendar</h2>

      <p>For thousands of years, the Chinese calendar needed no special name &mdash; it was simply <em>the</em> calendar (<span class="chinese-char">曆</span> <span class="pinyin">l&igrave;</span>). Each dynasty gave its official calendar a specific title &mdash; the <em>Taichu Calendar</em>, the <em>Shoushi Calendar</em>, the <em>Datong Calendar</em> &mdash; but no generic label was necessary because no competing system existed in daily life. That changed abruptly in 1912, and the naming confusion that followed persists to this day.</p>

      <h3>1912: Two Calendars, Two Names Required</h3>

      <p>On 2 January 1912, <span class="chinese-char">孫中山</span> <span class="pinyin">Sūn Zhōngshān</span> (Sun Yat-sen), provisional president of the newly founded Republic of China, decreed the adoption of the Gregorian calendar for official use. For the first time in Chinese history, two calendar systems coexisted &mdash; and both needed names to tell them apart.</p>

      <p>The Gregorian calendar acquired several labels: <span class="chinese-char">陽曆</span> <span class="pinyin">Y&aacute;ngl&igrave;</span> (&ldquo;solar calendar&rdquo;), <span class="chinese-char">新曆</span> <span class="pinyin">Xīnl&igrave;</span> (&ldquo;new calendar&rdquo;), <span class="chinese-char">西曆</span> <span class="pinyin">Xīl&igrave;</span> (&ldquo;Western calendar&rdquo;), <span class="chinese-char">公曆</span> <span class="pinyin">Gōngl&igrave;</span> (&ldquo;common calendar&rdquo;), and in Taiwan <span class="chinese-char">國曆</span> <span class="pinyin">Gu&oacute;l&igrave;</span> (&ldquo;national calendar&rdquo;). The traditional lunisolar calendar, meanwhile, was retroactively labelled with a grab-bag of informal names: <span class="chinese-char">舊曆</span> <span class="pinyin">Ji&ugrave;l&igrave;</span> (&ldquo;old calendar&rdquo;), <span class="chinese-char">陰曆</span> <span class="pinyin">Yīnl&igrave;</span> (&ldquo;lunar calendar&rdquo;), and eventually <span class="chinese-char">農曆</span> <span class="pinyin">N&oacute;ngl&igrave;</span> (&ldquo;agricultural calendar&rdquo;).</p>

      <div class="callout-box callout-box--jade">
        <div class="callout-icon">📜</div>
        <div class="callout-content">
          <h3>The Attempt to Ban the Old Calendar</h3>
          <p>The Nationalist Government went further than merely renaming. In 1928, Chiang Kai-shek formally <strong>abolished the traditional calendar</strong>, banned the printing of lunar-solar parallel calendars, and forbade Spring Festival celebrations. Government officials caught exchanging New Year greetings during the lunar new year faced punishment. The ban proved unenforceable &mdash; rural populations and urban residents alike continued to celebrate covertly &mdash; and was quietly repealed in 1934.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3><span class="chinese-char">農曆</span> <span class="pinyin">N&oacute;ngl&igrave;</span> &mdash; The &ldquo;Agricultural Calendar&rdquo;</h3>

      <p>The term <span class="chinese-char">農曆</span> is <strong>not an ancient name</strong>. It gained official status in 1947 when the Republic of China government rebranded the traditional calendar to emphasise its agricultural function. After 1949, the People&rsquo;s Republic of China retained the term. Today it is the standard label in mainland China, Hong Kong, and among overseas Chinese communities.</p>

      <p>The name carries an irony: the <em>agricultural</em> component of the Chinese calendar &mdash; the 24 Solar Terms that guide farming &mdash; is actually the <strong>solar</strong> component, not the lunar one. The months (which are lunar) have no particular agricultural significance. Calling the entire system the &ldquo;agricultural calendar&rdquo; is like naming a bicycle after only one of its wheels.</p>

      <h3><span class="chinese-char">陰曆</span> <span class="pinyin">Yīnl&igrave;</span> &mdash; The Misleading &ldquo;Lunar Calendar&rdquo;</h3>

      <div class="stat-highlight">
        <div class="stat-highlight-number"><span class="chinese-char">陰陽合曆</span></div>
        <div class="stat-highlight-text">
          The correct astronomical classification of the Chinese calendar is <strong>lunisolar</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">陰陽合曆</span> <span class="pinyin">Yīny&aacute;ng H&eacute;l&igrave;</span>) &mdash; a system that integrates <em>both</em> lunar months and solar positioning. Calling it <span class="chinese-char">陰曆</span> (&ldquo;lunar calendar&rdquo;) ignores the solar half entirely.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>The colloquial habit of calling the Chinese calendar <span class="chinese-char">陰曆</span> probably arose because the most visible feature &mdash; months beginning on the new moon, festivals falling on the 15th (full moon) &mdash; is lunar. But this is a fundamental misclassification. A true lunar calendar, such as the Islamic Hijri calendar, tracks <em>only</em> the moon. It has no intercalary correction and drifts through the seasons: Ramadan can fall in summer one decade and winter the next. The Chinese calendar, by contrast, uses the 24 Solar Terms and intercalary months precisely to <strong>prevent</strong> this drift. Its dual nature &mdash; lunar months anchored by solar terms &mdash; is its defining characteristic.</p>

      <h3>&ldquo;Lunar Calendar&rdquo; in English &mdash; A Mistranslation of a Misnomer</h3>

      <p>The English term &ldquo;lunar calendar&rdquo; for the Chinese system is a direct translation of the already-imprecise <span class="chinese-char">陰曆</span>. It compounds the error by stripping away the context that Chinese speakers at least implicitly understand &mdash; that <span class="chinese-char">陰曆</span> is shorthand, not a technical description. In English, &ldquo;lunar calendar&rdquo; is taken at face value, leading to the widespread but incorrect belief that the Chinese calendar is a purely lunar system.</p>

      <p>The correct English term is <strong>lunisolar calendar</strong>. The Chinese calendar shares this classification with the Hebrew calendar, the Hindu calendar, and the traditional Korean and Vietnamese calendars (which are historically derived from Chinese models). The Islamic Hijri calendar is the world&rsquo;s most widely used true lunar calendar.</p>

      <div class="callout-box callout-box--jade">
        <div class="callout-icon">🔍</div>
        <div class="callout-content">
          <h3>The &ldquo;Lunar New Year&rdquo; Controversy</h3>
          <p>Since 2012, the South Korean civic organisation VANK has campaigned to replace &ldquo;Chinese New Year&rdquo; with &ldquo;Lunar New Year&rdquo; in English-language media and international organisations, arguing that the holiday is shared across East Asia and should not bear China&rsquo;s name. The campaign has been successful with several Western brands and media outlets. However, the term &ldquo;Lunar New Year&rdquo; is <strong>astronomically incorrect</strong> &mdash; the Chinese calendar is lunisolar, not lunar &mdash; and it erases the Chinese origin of the calendar system from which the holiday derives. This site uses <strong>&ldquo;Chinese New Year&rdquo;</strong> or <strong>&ldquo;Spring Festival&rdquo;</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">春節</span> <span class="pinyin">Chūnji&eacute;</span>).</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>A Guide to the Names</h3>

      <table class="elements-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Name</th><th>Chinese</th><th>Literal Meaning</th><th>Refers To</th><th>Accuracy</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><span class="pinyin">N&oacute;ngl&igrave;</span></td><td>農曆</td><td>Agricultural calendar</td><td>Traditional Chinese calendar</td><td>Imprecise &mdash; the &ldquo;agricultural&rdquo; parts are solar</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="pinyin">Yīnl&igrave;</span></td><td>陰曆</td><td>Lunar calendar</td><td>Traditional Chinese calendar (colloquial)</td><td>Misleading &mdash; the calendar is lunisolar, not lunar</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="pinyin">Yīny&aacute;ng H&eacute;l&igrave;</span></td><td>陰陽合曆</td><td>Lunisolar calendar</td><td>The technical classification</td><td>Correct</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="pinyin">Ji&ugrave;l&igrave;</span></td><td>舊曆</td><td>Old calendar</td><td>Traditional Chinese calendar (informal)</td><td>Relative label, not descriptive</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="pinyin">Xi&agrave;l&igrave;</span></td><td>夏曆</td><td>Xia calendar</td><td>Traditional calendar (astronomical contexts)</td><td>Historically loaded &mdash; attributes the system to the legendary Xia dynasty</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="pinyin">Hu&aacute;ngl&igrave;</span></td><td>黃曆</td><td>Yellow (Emperor&rsquo;s) calendar / almanac</td><td>Traditional almanac with auspicious dates</td><td>Refers to the almanac, not the calendar system itself</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="pinyin">Gōngl&igrave;</span></td><td>公曆</td><td>Common calendar</td><td>Gregorian calendar</td><td>Standard PRC term for Gregorian</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="pinyin">Y&aacute;ngl&igrave;</span></td><td>陽曆</td><td>Solar calendar</td><td>Gregorian calendar (colloquial)</td><td>Correct in principle &mdash; the Gregorian is solar</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="pinyin">Gu&oacute;l&igrave;</span></td><td>國曆</td><td>National calendar</td><td>Gregorian calendar (Taiwan)</td><td>Jurisdiction-specific label</td></tr>
