      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="solar-terms">
      <h2>The 24 Solar Terms (<span class="chinese-char">二十四節氣</span> <span class="pinyin">Èrshísì Jiéqì</span>)</h2>

      <div class="image-panel">
        <img src="/img/photos/bamboo-forest.webp" alt="Lush bamboo forest representing the cycle of natural seasons" loading="lazy">
        <div class="image-panel-caption">
          <h3>24 Markers of the Sun's Path</h3>
          <p>UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage since 2016</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Historical Development</h3>
      <div class="timeline">
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <h3>Western Zhou (c. 1046–771 BCE)</h3>
          <p>Four cardinal terms established: two solstices (<span class="chinese-char">冬至</span> <span class="pinyin">Dōngzhì</span>, <span class="chinese-char">夏至</span> <span class="pinyin">Xiàzhì</span>) and two equinoxes (<span class="chinese-char">春分</span> <span class="pinyin">Chūnfēn</span>, <span class="chinese-char">秋分</span> <span class="pinyin">Qiūfēn</span>).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <h3>Spring and Autumn (770–476 BCE)</h3>
          <p>Expanded to 8 terms with the four seasonal beginnings (<span class="chinese-char">立春</span> <span class="pinyin">Lìchūn</span>, <span class="chinese-char">立夏</span> <span class="pinyin">Lìxià</span>, <span class="chinese-char">立秋</span> <span class="pinyin">Lìqiū</span>, <span class="chinese-char">立冬</span> <span class="pinyin">Lìdōng</span>).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <h3>Huainanzi (c. 139 BCE)</h3>
          <p>Complete 24-term system canonically described. The Northern Dipper's annual rotation marks each term in sequence.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <h3>Yi Xing — 729 CE</h3>
          <p>Introduced <strong>Dìngqì</strong> (true solar position) method, calculating each term by the sun's actual ecliptic longitude at 15° intervals.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <h3>Guo Shoujing — 1281 CE</h3>
          <p>The <em>Shoushi Calendar</em> fully adopted Dìngqì. Measured the tropical year at 365.2425 days — matching the Gregorian value 300 years earlier.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Jié vs. Qì</h3>
      <div class="comparison-grid">
        <div class="comparison-card comparison-card--gold">
          <h3>Jié (<span class="chinese-char">節</span> <span class="pinyin">Jié</span>) — Nodes</h3>
          <p>12 terms marking seasonal transitions and the beginning of each lunar month. Serve as boundary markers.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="comparison-card comparison-card--gold">
          <h3>Qì (<span class="chinese-char">氣</span> <span class="pinyin">Qì</span>) — Breaths</h3>
          <p>12 mid-month terms indicating peak seasonal characteristics. A month lacking a Qì becomes the <strong>intercalary month</strong>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Complete Reference Table</h3>
      <table class="elements-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Term</th><th>Chinese</th><th>Approx. Date</th><th>Type</th><th>Significance</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Lìchūn</td><td>立春</td><td>Feb 4</td><td>Jié</td><td>Start of Spring &mdash; Beginning of the agricultural year. The <em>Yueling</em> prescribes the emperor to ceremonially plough the first furrow.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Yǔshuǐ</td><td>雨水</td><td>Feb 19</td><td>Qì</td><td>Rain Water &mdash; Snow gives way to rain; ice thaws. Fields must be prepared for spring sowing.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Jīngzhé</td><td>驚蟄</td><td>Mar 6</td><td>Jié</td><td>Awakening of Insects &mdash; Spring thunder rouses dormant creatures. Originally called <span class="chinese-char">啟蟄</span> <span class="pinyin">Qǐzhé</span> in the Han Dynasty, renamed to avoid Emperor Jing's name taboo.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Chūnfēn</td><td>春分</td><td>Mar 21</td><td>Qì</td><td>Spring Equinox &mdash; Day and night of equal length. In the Zhou tradition, altars to the sun were tended on this date.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Qīngmíng</td><td>清明</td><td>Apr 5</td><td>Jié</td><td>Clear and Bright &mdash; Ancestral tomb-sweeping festival. Customs documented as early as the <em>Zuǒzhuàn</em> (<span class="chinese-char">左傳</span> <span class="pinyin">Zuǒzhuàn</span>), a Spring and Autumn period text.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Gǔyǔ</td><td>穀雨</td><td>Apr 20</td><td>Qì</td><td>Grain Rain &mdash; Last spring rains nourish newly planted crops. Associated with the legend of Cang Jie's invention of writing.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Lìxià</td><td>立夏</td><td>May 6</td><td>Jié</td><td>Start of Summer &mdash; Crops enter rapid growth. The <em>Yueling</em> records the emperor offering prayers to the God of the Stove.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Xiǎomǎn</td><td>小滿</td><td>May 21</td><td>Qì</td><td>Grain Buds &mdash; Grains begin to plump but are not yet ripe. Silkworms enter the cocoon-spinning stage.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Mángzhòng</td><td>芒種</td><td>Jun 6</td><td>Jié</td><td>Grain in Ear &mdash; Wheat is harvested, rice transplanted. The busiest period in the traditional farming calendar.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Xiàzhì</td><td>夏至</td><td>Jun 21</td><td>Qì</td><td>Summer Solstice &mdash; Longest day of the year. Among the earliest terms identified, confirmed by gnomon shadow measurements on Shang-era oracle bones.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Xiǎoshǔ</td><td>小暑</td><td>Jul 7</td><td>Jié</td><td>Minor Heat &mdash; Heat intensifies. The custom of &ldquo;drying books&rdquo; (<span class="chinese-char">曬書</span> <span class="pinyin">shàishū</span>) to prevent mildew dates to the Han Dynasty.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dàshǔ</td><td>大暑</td><td>Jul 23</td><td>Qì</td><td>Major Heat &mdash; Hottest period. The <em>Liji</em> describes seasonal adjustments to diet, favouring cooling foods and bitter herbs.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Lìqiū</td><td>立秋</td><td>Aug 7</td><td>Jié</td><td>Start of Autumn &mdash; First hints of autumn. The emperor made offerings in the western suburbs to welcome the season of harvest.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Chǔshǔ</td><td>處暑</td><td>Aug 23</td><td>Qì</td><td>End of Heat &mdash; Summer heat dissipates. Grain drying and storage begin. The <em>Nongzheng Quanshu</em> notes this as the deadline for late rice planting.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Báilù</td><td>白露</td><td>Sep 8</td><td>Jié</td><td>White Dew &mdash; Morning dew appears. The <em>Shījīng</em> (<span class="chinese-char">詩經</span> <span class="pinyin">Shījīng</span>, <em>Book of Songs</em>) contains the famous verse: &ldquo;White dew turns to frost&rdquo; (<span class="chinese-char">白露為霜</span> <span class="pinyin">Báilù wéi shuāng</span>).</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Qiūfēn</td><td>秋分</td><td>Sep 23</td><td>Qì</td><td>Autumn Equinox &mdash; Second equal day and night. Moon worship ceremonies were held, a precursor to the Mid-Autumn Festival.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hánlù</td><td>寒露</td><td>Oct 8</td><td>Jié</td><td>Cold Dew &mdash; Dew becomes cold. Chrysanthemum wine (<span class="chinese-char">菊花酒</span> <span class="pinyin">júhuājiǔ</span>) is brewed, a custom recorded in the Han-era <em>Xījīng Zájì</em> (<span class="chinese-char">西京雜記</span> <span class="pinyin">Xījīng Zájì</span>).</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Shuāngjiàng</td><td>霜降</td><td>Oct 23</td><td>Qì</td><td>Frost Descent &mdash; First frost appears. Persimmons are harvested and Chinese medicinal herbs are gathered. Military reviews were traditionally held.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Lìdōng</td><td>立冬</td><td>Nov 7</td><td>Jié</td><td>Start of Winter &mdash; Harvest complete, fields at rest. The emperor offered winter sacrifices. The <em>Yueling</em> prescribes sealing granaries and repairing city walls.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Xiǎoxuě</td><td>小雪</td><td>Nov 22</td><td>Qì</td><td>Minor Snow &mdash; Light snowfall begins in the north. Pickling vegetables and curing meats for winter storage commences.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dàxuě</td><td>大雪</td><td>Dec 7</td><td>Jié</td><td>Major Snow &mdash; Heavy snowfall. Rivers freeze. The custom of &ldquo;sealing the plough&rdquo; (<span class="chinese-char">封犁</span> <span class="pinyin">fēnglí</span>) marked the end of the farming year.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dōngzhì</td><td>冬至</td><td>Dec 22</td><td>Qì</td><td>Winter Solstice &mdash; Shortest day. In Zhou and Han times, this was the start of the new year. Grand court ceremonies were held; officials exchanged formal greetings.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Xiǎohán</td><td>小寒</td><td>Jan 6</td><td>Jié</td><td>Minor Cold &mdash; Cold intensifies. The &ldquo;Nine Nines&rdquo; counting custom (<span class="chinese-char">數九</span> <span class="pinyin">Shǔjiǔ</span>) begins from the Winter Solstice, tracking 81 days until spring.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dàhán</td><td>大寒</td><td>Jan 20</td><td>Qì</td><td>Major Cold &mdash; Coldest period. <a href="/spring-festival/">Spring Festival</a> preparations commence. The cycle completes and returns to Lìchūn.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="callout-box callout-box--jade">
        <div class="callout-icon">🌿</div>
        <div class="callout-content">
          <h3>Five Elements & Agricultural Wisdom</h3>
          <p>Each season of six terms corresponds to a <a href="/wuxing/">Five Element</a>: Spring/Wood, Summer/Fire, Autumn/Metal, Winter/Water, with Earth governing 18-day transitions. Proverbs like <span class="chinese-char">清明前後，種瓜點豆</span> <span class="pinyin">Qīngmíng qiánhòu, zhòng guā diǎn dòu</span> ("Around Qingming, plant melons and sow beans") encode generations of empirical knowledge. Xu Guangqi's Ming Dynasty <em>Nongzheng Quanshu</em> (1639) synthesised centuries of regional farming mapped to each term.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

